Introduction¶

I chose FBI Gun Dataset for this project. It provided two databases:

a) FBI Gun Data from Nov 1998 to Sep 2017. It contains the number of firearm checks (not sales) by month, state, and type. The data comes from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS). The NICS is used by to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Gun shops call into this system to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isn’t otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. Although this data does not provide actual gun sales, gun checks is still an indication of the volume of sales in each state over the years.

b) US Census Data. Most variables just have one data point per state (2016), but a few have data for more than one year.

Here are a few questions that could be answered by analyzing the two datasets.

1 - Comparison of firearm checks by state

2 - Anual trends of firearm checks

3 - Comparing hand-gun vs long-gun checks, and trends throuout years

4 - Gun checks compared to population, by state

5 - Is gun checks by state linked to % of Blacks, Hispanic, Asian, Whites (2016)

6 - Is gun checks by state linked to % Veterans (2016)

7 - Is gun checks by state linked to % of Foreign born persons (2016)

8 - Who buys more guns, women or men? and how is that changing over the years?

9 - Do we see a correlation with the education?

10 - How about a correlation with houseold income level?

11- Is percentege of persons in powerty correlated to gun checks?

12- What about employment? How do employment levels correlate with gun checks?

13- It would also ve very interseting to see how population density affects gun checks

14- And last: is time to work travel a factor?

I am going to answer these five:

1- Anual trends of firearm checks

2- Seasonality (monthly) trends for firearm checks in 2016. How has tha changed throughout the years? How 2016 compares to the monthly aggregated data from 1998-2017?

3- What state trend diferences can we see for firearm checks for the period 1998-2017? and for 2016 alone?

4- It is hard to draw any conclussions on gun state prevalence without bringing state population into the formula. I am going to make an analisys where I calculate the total number of gun permits for each state/1000 people

5- I also want to know if firearm permit checks is related to other factors like age, income level, education, gender and diversity

1) Format the date column so it is easier to work with. This way I will be able to select specific years and look at monthly trends.

2) Selected and organized the columns I will be working with.

3) Investigated the dataset to see if there were duplicates and nulls. We have no duplicates, but an insignificant number of nulls.

4) Substituted the nulls, first with zero values, then with the mean. It is better to use the mean values as substitutes for the nulls. The overall mean in each column is not affected as much.

##Cells containing percentage numbers are not consistent. To make them all consistent I will multiply those decimel
##number cells by 100. I create a function called multH (multiply by hundred). 
def multH(value):
    entero = value
    if value <1.0:
        entero = value *100.0
    return entero
In [688]:
##In this code below I am formating the data. getting rid of simbols (%, etc). Then, I turn them into numerical
##values. Then apply the multH function to the census_data file.
for x in USA_States:
    census_data[x].replace(regex=True, inplace=True, to_replace = r'[^\d.-]', value = r'')
    census_data[x] = pd.to_numeric(census_data[x], downcast='float', errors='ignore') 
    census_data[x] = census_data[x].apply(multH)

Combining and analyzing both datasets¶

Only in Utah, we see a decrease. Utah's firearm laws are some of the more permissive in the United States. In Utah, anyone over the age of 21 can carry a concealed weapon without a permit. Getting firearms in Utah is easier and easier every year.

In the above graph we can see that the states with the bigest growth in firearm permits per 1000 are: Kentucky, Indiana, Illinois, followed by New Hampshire, Wisconsin, Alabama and Minnesota. Hawaii is the lowest after Utah, but for very different reasons. Hawaii, with some of the nation’s toughest gun-related laws, keeps a tight rein on gun ownership, registration and use. Hawaii residents cannot purchase a firearm without first getting a permit to acquire the gun. People apply for those permits through the police department, and the department first checks local, state and national databases to see if the applicant has been convicted of a felony or a violent crime, including misdemeanor assaults or domestic violence charges.

Conclusions¶

When doing this analysis, I encountered a couple of limitations in our datafiles. First, firearm checks does not equate to firearm sales. Second, low numbers on firearm permit checks does not allways means less guns. In some cases it means the state has more relaxed gun laws. This is the case for Utah.

I observed steady annual increases in firearm permit checks. This is specially true in 2016.

I detected an increase in the number of firearm checks during December. This is traditionaly the biggest month in terms of retail sales. It obviously applies to firearms. It must be apopular gift.

Kentucky stood up in every analysis. In absolute, in relative to population and in 10 year growth numbers.

It was hard to see any correlation between the total number of firearm checks and race, age, income level, gender and education.
